	<div id="content">
		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Buffer overflow</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computer_security" title="Computer security">computer security</a> and <a href="/wiki/Computer_programming" title="Computer programming">programming</a>, a <b>buffer overflow</b>, or <b>buffer overrun</b>, is an <a href="/wiki/Anomaly_in_software" title="Anomaly in software">anomalous</a> condition where a <a href="/wiki/Process_(computing)" title="Process (computing)">process</a> attempts to store <a href="/wiki/Data" title="Data">data</a> beyond the boundaries of a fixed-length <a href="/wiki/Buffer_(computer_science)" title="Buffer (computer science)" class="mw-redirect">buffer</a>. The result is that the extra data overwrites adjacent <a href="/wiki/Computer_storage" title="Computer storage" class="mw-redirect">memory</a> locations. The overwritten data may include other buffers, variables and program flow data, and may result in erratic program behavior, a <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer memory">memory</a> access <a href="/wiki/Exception_handling" title="Exception handling">exception</a>, program termination (a <a href="/wiki/Crash_(computing)" title="Crash (computing)">crash</a>), incorrect results or ― especially if deliberately caused by a malicious user ― a possible breach of system security.</p>
<p>Buffer overflows can be triggered by inputs specifically designed to execute malicious code or to make the program operate in an unintended way. As such, buffer overflows cause many <a href="/wiki/Vulnerability_(computer_science)" title="Vulnerability (computer science)" class="mw-redirect">software vulnerabilities</a> and form the basis of many <a href="/wiki/Exploit_(computer_security)" title="Exploit (computer security)">exploits</a>. Sufficient <a href="/wiki/Bounds_checking" title="Bounds checking">bounds checking</a> by either the programmer, the <a href="/wiki/Compiler" title="Compiler">compiler</a> or the <a href="/wiki/Runtime" title="Runtime">runtime</a> can prevent buffer overflows.</p>
<p>The programming languages most commonly associated with buffer overflows are <a href="/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)">C</a> and <a href="/wiki/C%2B%2B" title="C++">C++</a>.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since March 2009" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup> They provide no built-in protection against accessing or overwriting data in any part of memory and do not check that data written to an array (the built-in buffer type) is within the boundaries of that array.</p>
<div class="noprint tright portal" style="border:solid #aaa 1px;margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 0.5em;">
